Spring WebFlux is a fully non-blocking, reactive web framework designed to handle a massive number of concurrent connections with very few threads.
Unlike standard Spring MVC (which uses a "Thread-per-Request" model), WebFlux uses an Event Loop architecture, similar to Node.js.

1. Core Architecture: Blocking vs. Non-Blocking
    Spring MVC (Servlet Stack)
    Model: One thread is dedicated to every single HTTP request.
    Bottleneck: If the thread has to wait for a database or an external API, it sits idle ("blocked"). 
            To handle 1,000 concurrent slow requests, you need 1,000 threads, which consumes a lot of memory (RAM).

Spring WebFlux (Reactive Stack)
    Model: A small, fixed number of threads (usually equal to CPU cores) handle all requests.
    Mechanism: When a request needs to wait for I/O (like a DB query), the thread registers a callback and moves on to handle the next request.
          When the DB is ready, an event is triggered, and a thread picks the work back up.

2. Key Components
    Project Reactor: The library providing the reactive foundation (Mono and Flux).
    Netty: The default high-performance, non-blocking server (replaces Tomcat).
    WebClient: The non-blocking, functional alternative to RestTemplate.
    Reactive Streams: The standard that ensures "Backpressure" (the consumer telling the producer to slow down so it doesn't get overwhelmed).

3. Implementation Styles
  WebFlux allows you to write code in two ways:
  A. Annotated Controllers (Familiar Style)
      Looks exactly like Spring MVC, but returns Mono or Flux. 
  B. Functional Endpoints (Modern Style)
      Uses Router Functions and Handler Functions. This is more lightweight and easier to test.

